Nobody goes to a fast-food joint for high cuisine, but you at least expect fried chicken to actually contain *chicken*. Cheap prices are not an excuse for deceptive behavior.

Similarly, when you pay $5 for a logo, you don't expect the next Nike swoosh, but you do expect to get some kind of original mark. But if last week's experiences is anything to go by, you'll most likely get low-quality stock artwork instead, or at best a sub-standard copy of somebody else's design.

At this point, is the job still worth even $5? Why not cut out the middleman and go buy your “logo” from iStockPhoto yourself?

### Fast Food Logos

Unethical business practices aside, I don't really have a problem with $5 logos. In a way, they fill a useful role in the design ecosystem: they let novice designers try their hand at client work, while providing a very cheap option for clients who don't want to spend too much.

